- VSCode Version: Code 1.13.1 (379d2efb5539b09112c793d3d9a413017d736f89, 2017-06-14T18:21:47.485Z)
- OS Version: Windows_NT ia32 6.1.7601
- Extensions: 

|Extension|Author|Version|
|---|---|---|
|perforce|slevesque|2.1.1|;


---

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Enter this code:
```ts
import * as React from 'react';

class F extends React.Component<void, void> {
    render() {
        <React.DOM.div 
    }
}
```

2. With the cursor at the end of 'React.DOM.div' press control-space to bring up intellisense suggestions.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13541817/27976670-8ec3679c-6335-11e7-8446-97997056ca81.png)

I see generic suggestions. I expect to see the props (properties, attributes) of div.

3. add to the code by typing className='abc' as below:
import * as React from 'react';

class F extends React.Component<void, void> {
    render() {
        <React.DOM.div className='abc'
    }
}

4. Place cursor at the end of 'abc'. Press control-space to get suggestions. Now you get suggestions for the props of div

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13541817/27976749-e8e08fb6-6335-11e7-85e9-e615d4f30e40.png)


This is the expected result in step 2 above. The issue is that the suggestions are not made until you have specified an initial attribute.


This same issue occurs for custom react components that are imported in a way that requires a dotted path. This can also be demonstrated by assigning to a local variable:

5. Enter this code:

import * as React from 'react';

interface FooProps {
    name: string;
    value: number;
}

class Foo extends React.Component<FooProps, void> {
    render() {
        return <div/>
    }
}

// This is atypical, but models import * as lib from 'mylib', and shows same behavior
let lib = {Foo: Foo};

class Usage extends React.Component<void, void> {
    render() { 
        return <lib.Foo
    }
}

6. Press control-space after lib.Foo. I expect to see props suggestions, but again just get generic suggestions.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13541817/27976868-56bfd3d4-6336-11e7-82ea-a1698c642a5b.png)


7. Add a property after lib.Foo (e.g. name='abc'), and then press control-space. This behaves as expected, showing suggestions for children, key, ref, and value.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13541817/27976926-87f3c654-6336-11e7-9765-f5e0d01fef29.png)

8. If instead of using 'lib.Foo' in step 5 you just reference 'Foo' directly, then the suggestions are as expected:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13541817/27976970-b08b33d6-6336-11e7-9f05-fa19ed05fa0c.png)


This is a major issue for our developers that are relying on intellisense for property suggestions with TSX, as many of our react components are imported using import * as vdl from 'VDL' and then referenced as vdl.VBox, vdl.Table, etc

Thank you for considering this issue.

To use, e.g. for the diff editor:

```typescript
vscode.commands.executeCommand(
  'vscode.diff',
  vscode.Uri.file('/Users/bpasero/Desktop/test-ts/CHANGELOG.md'),
  vscode.Uri.file('/Users/bpasero/Desktop/test-ts/package.json'),
  'title',
  {
    selection: new vscode.Range(new vscode.Position(1, 1), new vscode.Position(1, 2))
  }
);
```

For https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/30085
